name: Orbital Motion - 4
description: In this block we achieve 3 learning milestones: the significance of the Lamber theorem, properties of hyperbolic motion, and parabolic motion.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Chapter 2 - Summary
description: We go through the equations and diagrams that are worth memorising
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbital Motion - 2
description: We move from knowing only the angle - or "anomaly" - of the satellite location to knowing the timing of the motion using the Kepler Equation
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits in the Geocentric Frame
description: We move to 3D! Our orbits are embedded in coordinate frames - in particular into the geocentric equatorial frame in this case.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Shape of the Earth
description: After a repetition of how to calculate orbital elements from position and velocity, we discuss briefly how to describe the location of an object on the Earth's surface being a rotational ellipsoid
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits for Telecommunications 2
description: Final words on GTO, but how is GEO affected by perturbations?
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Reference Frames and Time
description: Reference Frames and Time
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Rocket Propulsion
description: The mechanics basics of rocket propulsion are explained and examples are given.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Applications and Tools
description: We finish the definition of reference times and go on to discuss the first application of reference frames: Calculating the time spent by a Satellite in Earth's shadow
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Rocket Propulsion 2
description: In block 37 we continue to discuss rocket propulsion by looking at what it takes to launch through a gravity well and using multiple stages.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Applications and Tools - 2
description: We finish chapter 3 with an example of a Space X launch and some theoretical considerations on state vector and  error propagation
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbital Transfers
description: Topic of this block are one and two manoeuvre transfers between orbits using rocket propulsion
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Transfer Optimality
description: Having calculated the Delta-v for a Hohmann transfer we look at other, potentially more optimal alternatives
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Chapter 3 Summary, Angular Momentum, and Moments of Inertia
description: After summarising chapter 3 we move into chapter 4 with the basics of a freely rotating extended body.
areas: Chapter 3 Summary, Angular Momentum, and Moments of Inertia
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Review Chapter 2 - 5
description: We recall formulas and concepts from chapters 2 to 5
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Principal Axes
description: Continuing rotational dynamics we describe the rigid body in its "natural" orientation, a.k.a. principal axes and consider the Euler equation of rotational dynamics together with the concept of Euler angles.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Summary Chap 6+
description: In this final block, the applications, rockets, and transfers are summarised
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Motion of the Spinning Top
description: We discover the complex motion of a simple system: the spinning top
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Spinning Satellites
description: We close off chapter 4 with a description of spinning-top motion as seen in the rest frame, stability issues for spinning satellites and an understanding of the Earth's rotation as it spins on its axis.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Summary Chapter 4, Introduction to Perturbations
description: With chapter 4 complete we turn our attention towards how small perturbations influence the orbital elements. The concepts of state vector, special perturbations, osculating trajectory, and osculating elements are introduced.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Osculating Conditions
description: Our entry into the world of perturbed orbits is the understanding of osculation conditions and the equations that lead to the drift of orbital elements. For two of the orbital elements - inclination and right ascension of ascending node - these drift equations are derived from basic geometric principles of infinitesimal perturbations on an orbit.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Lagrange Equations
description: Two variants of the Lagrange equations are presented: for perturbing accelerations and for perturbing potential. Both give us a tool to calculate the rate of change of orbital elements.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Other Perturbations
description: Closing chapter 5, we discuss three more of the physical phenomena that cause perturbations on a satellite's orbit: third body, solar radiation pressure, and relativistic effects.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Earth's Gravity
description: We move towards a mathematical framework describing the general gravity potential of a planet and end with the example of Earth.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Oblateness Perturbations
description: With our understanding of how to represent the irregular Earth's gravity field we focus on oblateness and its effects on semi-major axis and right ascension of ascending node
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Oblateness Perturbations - 2
description: We finish the discussion of changing orbital elements due to the oblateness of Earth. In order to put this into a useful recipe for predicting long-term the orbit (and thus position and velocity) of a satellite, a set of reference formulas is given without proof. This closes section 3 of chapter 5 of "Spaceflight Mechanics I"
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Introduction to Spaceflight Mechanics Winter Term 2021/2022
description: This video gives an insight what to expect in the lecture and what kind of topics will be covered.
areas: Introduction to Spaceflight Mechanics Winter Term 2021/2022
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: The Two-Body Problem
description: In this lecture you will make acquaintance with the principles of the idealised two-body problem and the equation of motion that describes it: the Newton equation.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Atmospheric Drag
description: The second physical perturbation phenomenon we are we discuss is atmospheric drag. In this block we develop the model of how to describe the atmosphere as a function of altitude in order to obtain the perturbing acceleration
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: The Kepler Problem
description: We describe the special case of a massive central body orbited by a point mass of negligible mass
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Atmospheric Drag 2
description: Putting it all together we arrive at the equations for change in semi-major axis and eccentricity for circular and elliptical orbits
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Integrals of Motion
description: We continue to discuss the Kepler problem with looking at conserved quantities also known as integrals of motion
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Atmospheric Drag 3
description: We finish the discussion of the effects of atmospheric drag by obtaining equations for the lifetime of a satellites and looking at a historic example: Sputnik II
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Elliptical Motion
description: We describe the case of elliptical motion around a central body with geometric parameters
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Basic Concepts Summary
description: In this block we wrap up all concepts discussed previously in order to prepare the transition into more applications-oriented discussions
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbital Motion
description: In this block we move away from a purely geometrical description of Kepler orbits towards a dynamic one. We will learn about the velocities: at perigee, at apogee, circular - and use them to calculate a useful relationship for the orbital energy. It is no surprise that the 2nd Kepler law is the basis of this work.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Molnyia and Tundra
description: In this block we discuss how to optimally place a telecommunications satellite for high-latitude customers
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits for Earth Observation
description: Satellites for Earth Observation are big business - let's look at how customer needs can be fulfilled by picking the most suitable orbit
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits for Telecommunication
description: Finishing off the Sun-Synchronous orbits with repeating ground-track, we move on to the most important commercial orbits of them all: the geostationary orbit.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbital Motion - 3
description: We learn how to look at orbital information in time and in position. Also, the first step in determining an orbit from initial conditions is made.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Impulse-Workshop Digitales Publizieren und gute wissenschaftliche Praxis
description: Der Workshop bietet einen Überblick über das Thema "Open Access (OA) und Digitales Publizieren an der TU Darmstadt". Zunächst werden die Leitlinien der Deutschen Forschungsgemeinschaft zur guten wissenschaftlichen Praxis erläutert.  Es folgt eine kurze Definition des Begriffes "OA" und eine Vorstellung der OA-Policy der TU. Weiterhin werden die entsprechenden Unterstützungsangebote der Universitäts- und Landesbibliothek Darmstadt präsentiert und die Themen "Autorenrechte" und "CC-Lizenzen" behandelt. Zum Schluss wird die Promotionsordnung der TU und das Thema Autorenidentifikation vorgestellt.
areas: Impulse-Workshop Digitales Publizieren und gute wissenschaftliche Praxis
author: [{'id': 374, 'firstName': 'Karen', 'lastName': 'Schiele', 'title': '', 'photoAvailable': False}]

name: Coffee Lecture "Autorenrechte - worauf sollten Sie achten?"
description: Coffee Lectures sind Kurzvorträge der ULB zu Themen rund um wissenschaftliches Arbeiten. In der Coffee Lecture "Autorenrechte" wird alles wichtige rund um das Thema "Autorenrechte" behandelt. Nach einer Definition der Urheber-Persönlichkeitsrechte und der Urheber-Verwertungsrechte folgen Einblicke in die Thematik "Rechteübertragung beim Abschluss von Verträgen" und das Zweitveröffentlichungsrecht.
areas: Coffee Lecture "Autorenrechte - worauf sollten Sie achten?"

name: Introduction to Spaceflight Mechanics Winter Term 2016/2017
description: This video gives an insight what to expect in the lecture and what kind of topics will be covered.
areas: Introduction to Spaceflight Mechanics Winter Term 2016/2017
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: The Two-Body Problem
description: In this lecture you will make acquaintance with the principles of the idealised two-body problem and the equation of motion that describes it: the Newton equation.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: The Kepler Problem
description: We describe the special case of a massive central body orbited by a point mass of negligible mass
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: The Kepler Problem - 2
description: We continue to discuss the Kepler problem
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Elliptical Motion
description: We describe the case of elliptical motion around a central body with geometric parameters
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbital Motion
description: In this block we move away from a purely geometrical description of Kepler orbits towards a dynamic one. We will learn about the velocities: at perigee, at apogee, circular - and use them to calculate a useful relationship for the orbital energy. It is no surprise that the 2nd Kepler law is the basis of this work.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Was ist, will und kann Mediendidaktik?
areas: Was ist, will und kann Mediendidaktik?
author: [{'id': 252, 'firstName': 'Petra', 'lastName': 'Grell', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbital Motion - 2
description: We move from knowing only the angle - or "anomaly" - of the satellite location to knowing the timing of the motion using the Kepler Equation
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbital Motion - 3
description: We learn how to look at orbital information in time and in position. Also, the first step in determining an orbit from initial conditions is made.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbital Motion - 4
description: In this block we achieve 3 learning milestones: the significance of the Lamber theorem, properties of hyperbolic motion, and parabolic motion.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Chapter 2 - Summary
description: We go through the equations and diagrams that are worth memorising
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits in the Geocentric Frame
description: We move to 3D! Our orbits are embedded in coordinate frames - in particular into the geocentric equatorial frame in this case.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Shape of the Earth
description: After a repetition of how to calculate orbital elements from position and velocity, we discuss briefly how to describe the location of an object on the Earth's surface being a rotational ellipsoid
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Reference Frames and Time
description: We encounter the topocentric horizon frame and the geocentric ecliptic frame. A discussion on the definition of time systems follows.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Applications and Tools
description: We finish the definition of reference times and go on to discuss the first application of reference frames: Calculating the time spent by a Satellite in Earth's shadow
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Allgemeine Didaktik als Orientierung für die Mediendidaktik
areas: Allgemeine Didaktik als Orientierung für die Mediendidaktik
author: [{'id': 252, 'firstName': 'Petra', 'lastName': 'Grell', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Applications and Tools - 2
description: We finish chapter 3 with an example of a Space X launch and some theoretical considerations on state vector and  error propagation
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Chapter 3 Summary, Angular Momentum, and Moments of Inertia
description: After summarising chapter 3 we move into chapter 4 with the basics of a freely rotating extended body.
areas: Chapter 3 Summary, Angular Momentum, and Moments of Inertia
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Principal Axes
description: Continuing rotational dynamics we describe the rigid body in its "natural" orientation, a.k.a. principal axes and consider the Euler equation of rotational dynamics together with the concept of Euler angles.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Motion of the Spinning Top
description: We discover the complex motion of a simple system: the spinning top
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Summary Chapter 4, Introduction to Perturbations
description: With chapter 4 complete we turn our attention towards how small perturbations influence the orbital elements. The concepts of state vector, special perturbations, osculating trajectory, and osculating elements are introduced.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Lerntheorien als Orientierung für die Mediendidaktik
areas: Lerntheorien als Orientierung für die Mediendidaktik
author: [{'id': 252, 'firstName': 'Petra', 'lastName': 'Grell', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Osculating Conditions
description: Our entry into the world of perturbed orbits is the understanding of osculation conditions and the equations that lead to the drift of orbital elements. For two of the orbital elements - inclination and right ascension of ascending node - these drift equations are derived from basic geometric principles of infinitesimal perturbations on an orbit.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Spinning Satellites
description: We close off chapter 4 with a description of spinning-top motion as seen in the rest frame, stability issues for spinning satellites and an understanding of the Earth's rotation as it spins on its axis.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Lagrange Equations
description: Two variants of the Lagrange equations are presented: for perturbing accelerations and for perturbing potential. Both give us a tool to calculate the rate of change of orbital elements.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Earth's Gravity
description: We move towards a mathematical framework describing the general gravity potential of a planet and end with the example of Earth.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Lerntheorien als Orientierung für die Mediendidaktik
areas: Lerntheorien als Orientierung für die Mediendidaktik
author: [{'id': 252, 'firstName': 'Petra', 'lastName': 'Grell', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Oblateness Perturbations
description: With our understanding of how to represent the irregular Earth's gravity field we focus on oblateness and its effects on semi-major axis and right ascension of ascending node
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Oblateness Perturbations - 2
description: We finish the discussion of changing orbital elements due to the oblateness of Earth. In order to put this into a useful recipe for predicting long-term the orbit (and thus position and velocity) of a satellite, a set of reference formulas is given without proof. This closes section 3 of chapter 5 of "Spaceflight Mechanics I"
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Atmospheric Drag
description: The second physical perturbation phenomenon we are we discuss is atmospheric drag. In this block we develop the model of how to describe the atmosphere as a function of altitude in order to obtain the perturbing acceleration
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Studien zum Einsatz digitaler Medien in der Schule
areas: Studien zum Einsatz digitaler Medien in der Schule
author: [{'id': 252, 'firstName': 'Petra', 'lastName': 'Grell', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Atmospheric Drag 2
description: Putting it all together we arrive at the equations for change in semi-major axis and eccentricity for circular and elliptical orbits
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Atmospheric Drag 3
description: We finish the discussion of the effects of atmospheric drag by obtaining equations for the lifetime of a satellites and looking at a historic example: Sputnik II
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Other Perturbations
description: Closing chapter 5, we discuss three more of the physical phenomena that cause perturbations on a satellite's orbit: third body, solar radiation pressure, and relativistic effects.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Basic Concepts Summary
description: In this block we wrap up all concepts discussed previously in order to prepare the transition into more applications-oriented discussions
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits for Earth Observation

name: Orbits for Telecommunication

name: Orbital Motion
description: In this block we move away from a purely geometrical description of Kepler orbits towards a dynamic one. We will learn about the velocities: at perigee, at apogee, circular - and use them to calculate a useful relationship for the orbital energy. It is no surprise that the 2nd Kepler law is the basis of this work.

name: Orbital Motion - 3

collection: [{'id': 195, 'name': 'Wind-, Wasser-, Wellenkraft - Optimierung und Skalierung von Fluidsystemen'}]

name: Applications and Tools
description: We finish the definition of reference times and go on to discuss the first application of reference frames: Calculating the time spent by a Satellite in Earth's shadow
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Principal Axes
description: Continuing rotational dynamics we describe the rigid body in its "natural" orientation, a.k.a. principal axes and consider the Euler equation of rotational dynamics together with the concept of Euler angles.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Shape of the Earth
description: After a repetition of how to calculate orbital elements from position and velocity, we discuss briefly how to describe the location of an object on the Earth's surface being a rotational ellipsoid
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Applications and Tools - 2
description: We finish chapter 3 with an example of a Space X launch and some theoretical considerations on state vector and  error propagation
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Chapter 3 Summary, Angular Momentum, and Moments of Inertia
description: After summarising chapter 3 we move into chapter 4 with the basics of a freely rotating extended body.
areas: Chapter 3 Summary, Angular Momentum, and Moments of Inertia
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Chapter 4 Summary, Introduction to Perturbations
description: With chapter 4 complete we turn our attention towards how small perturbations influence the orbital elements. The concepts of state vector, special perturbations, osculating trajectory, and osculating elements are introduced.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Betz
author: [{'id': 1, 'firstName': 'Peter', 'lastName': 'Pelz', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': True}]
collection: [{'id': 195, 'name': 'Wind-, Wasser-, Wellenkraft - Optimierung und Skalierung von Fluidsystemen'}]

name: Motion of the Spinning Top
description: We discover the complex motion of a simple system: the spinning top
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Spinning Satellites
description: We close off chapter 4 with a description of spinning-top motion as seen in the rest frame, stability issues for spinning satellites and an understanding of the Earth's rotation as it spins on its axis.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Lagrange Equations
description: Two variants of the Lagrange equations are presented: for perturbing accelerations and for perturbing potential. Both give us a tool to calculate the rate of change of orbital elements.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Earth's Gravity
description: We move towards a mathematical framework describing the general gravity potential of a planet and end with the example of Earth.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Osculating Conditions
description: Our entry into the world of perturbed orbits is the understanding of osculation conditions and the equations that lead to the drift of orbital elements. For two of the orbital elements - inclination and right ascension of ascending node - these drift equations are derived from basic geometric principles of infinitesimal perturbations on an orbit.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Atmospheric Drag 2
description: Putting it all together we arrive at the equations for change in semi-major axis and eccentricity for circular and elliptical orbits
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Erster Hauptsatz
author: [{'id': 1, 'firstName': 'Peter', 'lastName': 'Pelz', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': True}]
collection: [{'id': 195, 'name': 'Wind-, Wasser-, Wellenkraft - Optimierung und Skalierung von Fluidsystemen'}]

name: Atmospheric Drag 3
description: We finish the discussion of the effects of atmospheric drag by obtaining equations for the lifetime of a satellites and looking at a historic example: Sputnik II
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Oblateness Perturbations - 2
description: We finish the discussion of changing orbital elements due to the oblateness of Earth. In order to put this into a useful recipe for predicting long-term the orbit (and thus position and velocity) of a satellite, a set of reference formulas is given without proof. This closes section 3 of chapter 5 of "Spaceflight Mechanics I"
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Komplexe Zahlen und Grenzwerte bei Funktionen
areas: Komplexe Zahlen und Grenzwerte bei Funktionen
author: [{'id': 76, 'firstName': 'Robert', 'lastName': 'Haller-Dintelmann', 'title': 'Dr.', 'photoAvailable': False}]

name: Vorlesung 03.12.2015
author: [{'id': 1, 'firstName': 'Peter', 'lastName': 'Pelz', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': True}]
collection: [{'id': 195, 'name': 'Wind-, Wasser-, Wellenkraft - Optimierung und Skalierung von Fluidsystemen'}]

name: Other Perturbations
description: Closing chapter 5, we discuss three more of the physical phenomena that cause perturbations on a satellite's orbit: third body, solar radiation pressure, and relativistic effects.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Oblateness Perturbations
description: With our understanding of how to represent the irregular Earth's gravity field we focus on oblateness and its effects on semi-major axis and right ascension of ascending node
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Atmospheric Drag
description: The second physical perturbation phenomenon we are we discuss is atmospheric drag. In this block we develop the model of how to describe the atmosphere as a function of altitude in order to obtain the perturbing acceleration
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Basic Concepts Summary
description: In this block we wrap up all concepts discussed previously in order to prepare the transition into more applications-oriented discussions
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Vorlesung 13.01.2016
author: [{'id': 1, 'firstName': 'Peter', 'lastName': 'Pelz', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': True}]
collection: [{'id': 195, 'name': 'Wind-, Wasser-, Wellenkraft - Optimierung und Skalierung von Fluidsystemen'}]

name: Molnyia and Tundra
description: In this block we discuss how to optimally place a telecommunications satellite for high-latitude customers
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits for Earth Observation
description: Satellites for Earth Observation are big business - let's look at how customer needs can be fulfilled by picking the most suitable orbit
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits for Telecommunication
description: Finishing off the Sun-Synchronous orbits with repeating ground-track, we move on to the most important commercial orbits of them all: the geostationary orbit.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Vorlesung 27.01.2016
author: [{'id': 1, 'firstName': 'Peter', 'lastName': 'Pelz', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': True}]
collection: [{'id': 195, 'name': 'Wind-, Wasser-, Wellenkraft - Optimierung und Skalierung von Fluidsystemen'}]

name: Orbits for Telecommunication 3
description: Wrapping up Chapter 6 of the book we look at the libration motion adopted by a GEO satellite when left alone on GEO
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbits for Telecommunication 2
description: Final words on GTO, but how is GEO affected by perturbations?
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Transfer Optimality
description: Having calculated the Delta-v for a Hohmann transfer we look at other, potentially more optimal alternatives
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Orbit Transfer
description: Topic of this block are one and two manoeuvre transfers between orbits using rocket propulsion
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Rocket Propulsion
description: The mechanics basics of rocket propulsion are explained and examples are given.
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Review Chapter 2 - 5
description: We recall formulas and concepts from chapters 2 to 5
author: [{'id': 248, 'firstName': 'Markus', 'lastName': 'Landgraf', 'title': 'Dr. rer. nat.', 'photoAvailable': True}]

name: Rocket Propulsion 2
description: In block 37 we continue to discuss rocket propulsion by looking at what it takes to launch through a gravity well and using multiple stages.

name: Europäischer Betriebsrat, Weltbetriebsrat  Chancen und Grenzen
description:
In globalen Konzernen benötigt auch die Vertretung von Beschäftigteninteressen eine globale Dimension.
Eine EU-Richtlinie schuf vor knapp 20 Jahren die gesetzliche Grundlage für Informations- und Konsultationsrechte von Europäischen Betriebsräten. Mittlerweile gibt es in einigen Konzernen auch auf globaler
Ebene eine Zusammenarbeit von Arbeitnehmervertretern, Gewerkschaften und Management. Der Vortrag
gibt Einblicke in die praktischen Erfahrungen bei Opel/Vauxhall und General Motors.

Produktionsbeziehungen entwickelt. Unter Bezug auf die wachsenden Sozial- und Arbeitskonflikte der
letzten Jahre werden Perspektiven zu arbeitspolitischen Reformen in China diskutiert.

name: Internationale Beziehungen der TU Darmstadt & Studentenwerk interkulturell
description:
Rund 245.000 internationale Studierende sind in Deutschland immatrikuliert, davon
rund 108.000 aus Staaten außerhalb der EU. Vor dem Hintergrund zunehmender
interkultureller Öffnung auch in Darmstadt steht das Studentenwerk als sozialer
Partner der Hochschulen vor neuen Herausforderungen und Aufgaben: Es leistet
Integrationsarbeit, fördert den interkulturellen Dialog, erleichtert ausländischen
Studierenden den Einstieg ins Studium und unterstützt sie im Alltag.
Christina Wendt war bis Ende Oktober 2012 Bereichsleiterin des Wohnservice im Studentenwerk. Seit November 2012 ist sie
betraut mit der Aufgabe der Errichtung eines neuen Bereichs Beratung - Interkultureller Austausch und Kommunikation.

name: Einführung, Hat die Arbeit eine Zukunft?
description:
Die erste Veranstaltung führt in die Thematik und die Organisation bzw. den weiteren Ablauf der Veranstaltung ein.
Hat die Arbeit eine Zukunft?  Was bedeutet das Wort Arbeit eigentlich? Die Frage lässt sich im Rückblick auf das 19. Jahrhundert beantworten. Aber nach der klassischen Bedeutung von Arbeit handelt es sich nicht um etwas Veränderbares  wie kommen wir also darauf, heute von der Zukunft und der Gestaltung von Arbeit zu reden?
areas: Einführung, Hat die Arbeit eine Zukunft?

name: Themenfelder zukünftiger Arbeit
description: In dieser Veranstaltung werden Trends zukünftiger Arbeitswelten vorgestellt. Hierbei wird u.a. auf die Themen: Gesundheit, demographische Entwicklung und Work-Life-Balance eingegangen.
author: [{'id': 44, 'firstName': 'Ralph', 'lastName': 'Bruder', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': False}, {'id': 105, 'firstName': 'Karin', 'lastName': 'Diegelmann', 'title': 'Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': False}]

name: Flexibilisierung und Prekarisierung von Arbeit
description: Flexibilität gehört heute zu den (vermeintlichen) selbstverständlichen Notwendigkeiten der Arbeitswelt. Unternehmen müssen sich beständig ihren Märkten anpassen und die Beschäftigten ihren Unternehmen. Der Anteil der Normalarbeitsverhältnisse an der Gesamtbeschäftigung wird kleiner. Neue Beschäftigungsformen wie z. B. Zeitarbeit nehmen zu. Die Unternehmen fordern weitere Spielräume für den flexiblen Einsatz von Arbeit, um im Wettbewerb bestehen zu können. Erst allmählich rücken problematische Folgen dieser Arbeits- und Beschäftigungsformen in den Fokus, die u.a. mit einer Prekarisierung von Arbeit und Beschäftigung gefasst werden können.
author: [{'id': 105, 'firstName': 'Karin', 'lastName': 'Diegelmann', 'title': 'Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': False}, {'id': 108, 'firstName': 'Rudi', 'lastName': 'Schmiede', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.', 'photoAvailable': False}]

name: Programmiersprachen und -techniken
description: Programmiersprachen und -techniken Der Kurs Programmiersprachen und  techniken vertieft die Inhalte der Vorlesung "Grundlagen der elektronischen Datenverarbeitung" aus dem Themengebiet "Methoden der Programmierung". Vermittelt werden vor allem Kenntnisse aus den Bereichen Dateioperationen, graphische Schnittstellen und Algorithmen in MATLAB. Zusätzlich wird eine (kurze) Einführung in die objektorientierte Programmierung in Verbindung mit modernen Entwicklungsumgebungen gegeben.
author: [{'id': 104, 'firstName': 'Reiner', 'lastName': 'Anderl', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': False}]

name: Gute Arbeit - Entwicklungstendenzen von Arbeit
description: Individuen brauchen Rückhalt in Kollektiven und Institutionen. Es genügt nicht, den Menschen Ratschläge zu geben, wie sie fit bleiben für Beruf und Arbeitsmarkt. Die Erosion dieses Rückhalts ist einer der wichtigsten Gründe für die Zunahme von Stress und Burn-Out. Belastungen sind als gesellschaftliches Problem zu begreifen. Gute Arbeit ist ein politisches Programm. Im Vortrag werden die wichtigsten Entwicklungstendenzen von Arbeit analysiert, und es werden Ansatzpunkte benannt für die künftige Gestaltung guter Arbeit.
author: [{'id': 111, 'firstName': 'Klaus', 'lastName': 'Kock', 'title': 'Dr.', 'photoAvailable': False}]

name: Einführung in das rechnergestützte Programmieren
description: Einführung in das rechnergestützte Programmieren Zu den Inhalten der gesamten Lehrveranstaltung zählen neben dem Schwerpunkt der 3D-CAD Techniken (NX 8) auch Grundlagen im Produktdatenmanagement (Teamcenter 8.3 UA) sowie in der Erstellung von Handskizzen und technischen Produktdokumentationen. Zusätzlich lernen die Studierenden die elementaren DIN-/ISO Normen kennen und sammeln durch die gruppengebundene Bearbeitung der Aufgabenstellungen Erfahrungen im für den modernen Ingenieur wichtigen teamorientierten Arbeiten. Alle für die Ausbildung erforderlichen Lehrunterlagen und Informationen werden den Studenten in digitaler Form auf den vorliegenden Webseiten zur Verfügung gestellt.
author: [{'id': 104, 'firstName': 'Reiner', 'lastName': 'Anderl', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': False}]

name: Ganzheitliche Produktionssysteme verändern die Arbeitswelt I - Video
description: Immer schlanker, immer schneller: Ganzheitliche Produktionssysteme verändern die Arbeitswelt. Unter dem Schlagwort ganzheitliches Produktionssystem werden Produktionsprozesse zunehmend nach dem Vorbild Toyotas umgestaltet. Die bringt für die Beschäftigten erhebliche Veränderungen mit sich. Betroffen sind nicht nur die Produktion, sondern auch die Angestelltenbereiche einschließlich der Produktentwicklung. Betriebe stehen vor der Herausforderung, ganzheitliche Produktionssysteme so zu gestalten, dass sie gleichermaßen den Ansprüchen an Wirtschaftlichkeit und Gesichtspunkten einer menschengerechten Arbeitsgestaltung gerecht werden.
areas: Ganzheitliche Produktionssysteme verändern die Arbeitswelt I - Video
author: [{'id': 107, 'firstName': 'Thomas', 'lastName': 'Balzer', 'title': 'M.A.', 'photoAvailable': False}, {'id': 109, 'firstName': 'Detlef', 'lastName': 'Gerst', 'title': 'Dr.', 'photoAvailable': False}]

name: CAD-/CAM-Prozesskette in der Prozesslernfabrik CiP
description: CAD-/CAM-Prozesskette in der Prozesslernfabrik CiP Im Rahmen des Tutoriums CAD-/CAM-Prozesskette in der Prozesslernfabrik CiP wird Studenten eine Einführung in das Manufacturing-Modul von NX gegeben. Ziel ist die Vermittlung des Verständnisses der Prozesskette CAD-NC. Hierfür wird sowohl auf die Methoden und Prinzipien der CAD-Modellierung wie auch die Methoden und Prinzipien bei der Erstellung von NC-Steuerdaten eingegangen. Das Tutorium schließt mit der von Studenten selbständig durchgeführten Fräsbearbeitung des modellierten Produktes ab.
author: [{'id': 104, 'firstName': 'Reiner', 'lastName': 'Anderl', 'title': 'Prof. Dr.-Ing.', 'photoAvailable': False}]

Betriebe stehen vor der Herausforderung, ganzheitliche Produktionssysteme so zu gestalten, dass sie gleichermaßen den Ansprüchen an Wirtschaftlichkeit und Gesichtspunkten einer menschengerechten Arbeitsgestaltung gerecht werden.
